  "text": "The Kafka producer record batch timeout error originates from the `org.apache.kafka.common.errors.TimeoutException` class (github.com/sg-evals/kafka--0753c489, clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/common/errors/TimeoutException.java). The timeout exception is thrown with the error message 'Expiring N record(s) for topic-partition' when record batches expire.\n\nThe record batch expiration is controlled by the `delivery.timeout.ms` configuration parameter defined as `DELIVERY_TIMEOUT_MS_CONFIG` constant in ProducerConfig.java (line 165). This configuration specifies an upper bound on the time to report success or failure after a call to send() returns.\n\nThe batch expiration logic is implemented in two locations:\n\n1. RecordAccumulator.expiredBatches() (line 465) - Returns batches in the accumulator that have reached the delivery timeout threshold.\n\n2. Sender.getExpiredInflightBatches() (line 180) - Returns in-flight batches (already sent to broker) that have reached the delivery timeout.\n\nBoth methods use the ProducerBatch.hasReachedDeliveryTimeout() method (line 438 in ProducerBatch.java) to check if a batch has exceeded the delivery timeout. This method compares the elapsed time since batch creation (now - createdMs) against the deliveryTimeoutMs threshold.\n\nWhen expired batches are detected in Sender.sendProducerData() (around line 405-423), the error message 'Expiring {recordCount} record(s) for {topicPartition}: {elapsedMs} ms has passed since batch creation' is constructed (line 416-417) and a TimeoutException is thrown via failBatch() to notify the user of the timeout."
}

